BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ZMPCdZtw6qnFsCXxeAaqf
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - A
	ll Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nJ1FTx5HyF51HKIgAyZ9C
SUMMARY:Kameelah Janan Rasheed: we leak\, we exceed
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Kameelah Janan Rasheed \\(b. 1985\, East Palo Alto\, CA\; lives
	 and works in Brooklyn\, NY\\) is a self-described “learner” who creates m
	ulti-media works that explore the poetics-pleasures-politics of Black know
	ledge production\, information technologies\, \\[un\\]learning\, and belie
	f formation. She often integrates found images and words alongside her own
	 writing to create collaged wall installations and experimental video work
	s. Across her work\, Rasheed investigates the revision and life cycles of 
	text\, embracing expanded and embodied forms of writing and reading.\n\nwe
	 leak\, we exceed will activate the unique volume and multiple vantage poi
	nts of the Henry’s double-height gallery\, drawing together threads from p
	hysics\, Black critical thought\, and information theory to create an imme
	rsive environment that interrogates the spatial and social implications of
	 compression. A common process used in data storage\, spatial organization
	\, and information systems\, compression abbreviates and collapses complex
	 ideas into more simplified forms. Rasheed questions the way compression c
	omes at the cost of nuance and creates unrecoverable losses. She draws par
	allels between the compression of information and the containment of peopl
	e\, both physically and through the structuring and defining of identities
	. Through a network of video\, sound\, and architectural mark-making\, Ras
	heed proposes alternatively what she calls “an embrace of Black excess and
	 expansion” as a liberatory practice.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/kameelah-janan-rasheed-we
	-leak-we-exceed/16417090/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:6PT8Kq4k2EROrDOG1qlKP
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nffY-zoAX_v-QOTm0DDWy
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Cul
	ture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:KULNKZ2IBMGv30jsWPkbd
SUMMARY:Amplify: a hands-on marketing workshop for artists
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Event Types: Arts\,Community\,Education\,Special Events\,Tra in
	ing-Classes/Workshops\,Youth\n\nNeighborhoods: Citywide\,Pioneer Squar e\n
	\nContact: Rana San\n\nContact Phone: \\(206\\) 256-6279\n\nContact Email:
	 rana.san@seattle.gov\n\nAudience: All\n\nPre-Register: No\n\nCost: Free\n
	\nArtists of all disciplines and career stages benefit from building a str
	ong toolkit to promote their work\, apply for funding and residencies\, an
	d pursue press opportunities. In this free two-day intensive \, you'll lea
	rn foundational marketing skills and create resources you can use right aw
	ay.\n\nThrough hands-on activities and e xpert QandAs\, you'll:\n\nDraft o
	r refresh your artist bi o and project description\n\nCreate a clear strat
	egy for digital and social media marketing\n\nLearn to present your work a
	nd organize your materials\n\nGain insights from industry pros\n\nReceive 
	a free professional headshot\n\nMake con nections with fellow Seattle arti
	sts\n\nYou'll walk away with concrete tools\, organized assets\, and renew
	ed confidence to share your work with the world.\n\nSchedule:\n\nFeb. 21 a
	nd 22\n\n10 a.m. - 5 p.m. \\(Lunch break included\\) 0\;\n\nDoors open at 
	9:30 a.m.\n\nAbout the facil itators:\n\nTiffany N. Tomkinson\n\nSeattle P
	hotographer\, Video Producer\, Photojournalist\n\nGro wing up 4th generati
	on in the printing industry and starting my own DIY print zine as a teenag
	er\, Tiffany has been inspired by the power of visual imagery to convey au
	thentic human experience. Today Tiffany works as a professional photograph
	er\, video producer\, and photojournalist in t he greater Seattle area. Ti
	ffany works with musicians\, artists\, and or ganizations to produce photo
	 and video campaigns from creative conception to completion.\n\nTiffany's 
	work has been featured in a number of prominent Northwest outlets\, includ
	ing KEXP\, YES! Magazine \, NPR\, King 5's Evening Magazine\, Seattle Rock
	 Orchestra\, and t he Leukemia and Lymphoma Society.\n\ncenterpointphotogr
	aphy.com\n\n| IG:\n\n@center.point.photography\n\nShaudi Bianca Vahdat\n\n
	Composer\, songwriter\, performer\, and digital and social media marketing
	 special ist\n\nShaudi Bianca Vahdat specializes in digital and s ocial me
	dia marketing for independent artists and organizations. She consults on c
	ontent strategy\, branding\, and campaigns that help artists c onnect with
	 audiences by sharing their work authentically. She is also a freelance wr
	iter for The Wrapbook Blog\, where she covers a range of topics for filmma
	kers.\n\nShaudi is also a musician\, composer and theatre artist. She has 
	performed and/or composed for organizations like Washington Ensemble Theat
	re\, Book-It Repertory Theatre\, The Bushw ick Book Club\, Seattle Arts an
	d Lectures\, and Opera House Arts in S tonington\, Maine. She served as a 
	Fall 2024 Artist-in-Residence at Inscape Arts\, and presented her original
	 musical The Golden Door: an American immigrant song cycle in 2025 at Seat
	tle Center as part of the Artists at the Center program as well as an enco
	re co-production with Seattle Open Arts Place. She is also a current advis
	or for the City of Seattle's ARTS at King Street Station program.\n\nShaud
	i holds a Master of Music in Contemporary Performance from Berklee College
	 of Music and a B.A. in Drama Performance from the University of Washingto
	n Seattle.\n\nshaudibiancavahdat.com\n\n| IG:\n\n@shaudibianca\n\nAbout th
	e series:\n\nThe\n\ncommUNITY series\n\nis a selection of free public prog
	rams that center connection\, career development\, and the co-creation of 
	art. Curated by\n\nARTS at King Street Station Advisors \, this series bri
	ngs together their visions and talents to build community\, engage attende
	es in powerful arts practices\, and offer free career development and skil
	l-building for all ages. This series features workshops by Ashanti Davis\,
	 Alicia Mullikin\, Shaudi Vahdat\, Scott Oshima\, and Marie Kidhe.\n\nFrom
	 SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/amplify-a-hands-on-market
	ing-workshop-for-artists/17661051/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:ARTS at King Street Station\, 303 S. Jackson Street\, Top Floo r\,
	 Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:V81LeJea_RKolJcobp_cN
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260214T003621Z
DTSTART:20260222T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - A
	rts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-02-22T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
